    "client_msg_id": "874d54d9-4de2-4f42-923d-a422d9646f30",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "I read it many years ago. As a physicist and Tai-Chi practitioner, I can confirm pretty much everything it says about physics and taoism. The analogies are well observed - what you make of them is up to you of course.\n\nI had a math professor at university who held a lecture every year drawing similar analogies between the creation story of the bible and the scientific story of the formation of the Earth and its biosphere. He observed in particular that the order of appearance of everything was the same.\n\nPersonally I find Capra's analogies more interesting than those of my math professor, but then, that's mostly a matter of personal appreciation.",
    "user": "UJBAJNFLK",
    "ts": "1685692359.461379",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "rMZTa",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "I read it many years ago. As a physicist and Tai-Chi practitioner, I can confirm pretty much everything it says about physics and taoism. The analogies are well observed - what you make of them is up to you of course.\n\nI had a math professor at university who held a lecture every year drawing similar analogies between the creation story of the bible and the scientific story of the formation of the Earth and its biosphere. He observed in particular that the order of appearance of everything was the same.\n\nPersonally I find Capra's analogies more interesting than those of my math professor, but then, that's mostly a matter of personal appreciation."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1685663214.419819",
    "parent_user_id": "U055V4HCHU7",
    "channel_name": "linking-together",
    "channel_id": "C5U3SEW6A"
  },
  {
    "client_msg_id": "72b7c534-e440-46e5-a61d-3cf2e9c89525",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "<@U0296ACR13M> I think one of the observations is that you don’t need all the code to do a specific task.\n\nUsually you need knowledge of the small subset of the codebase to accomplish the specific task - and part of the work is just scoping the task itself.\n\nMagnet lets you have control over what the right context for the task at hand is, by letting you manually select the files you want to tell the LLM about.\n\nWe’re working on having Magnet help in the file-selection part of the workflow too, where at least we can suggest what files are likely relevant based on the prompt",
    "user": "U6S1R1M6K",
    "ts": "1685702358.151799",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "frYE0",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "user",
                "user_id": "U0296ACR13M"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " I think one of the observations is that you don’t need all the code to do a specific task.\n\nUsually you need knowledge of the small subset of the codebase to accomplish the specific task - and part of the work is just scoping the task itself.\n\nMagnet lets you have control over what the right context for the task at hand is, by letting you manually select the files you want to tell the LLM about.\n\nWe’re working on having Magnet help in the file-selection part of the workflow too, where at least we can suggest what files are likely relevant based on the prompt"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
